# Not allowed to inject her own insulin
Down the phone, the man’s words spilled out in a wave of anger and concern.
“She’s in hospital,” he explained, distress sharpening his voice as he
described what was happening to his beloved wife.
“She wasn’t allowed to inject her own insulin. It wasn’t being given at the
right time. Her blood glucose levels weren’t being tested often enough. She
collapsed because she wasn’t getting her meds on time. They’ve had to rush her
 __ This was the worrying story one man shared with the Policy and Advocacy
The team's job is to speak up for the specific needs of people living with
diabetes to help remove hurdles that make their lives harder.
In hospitals, staff are required to manage and administer all medicines. This
means people living with diabetes are not permitted to inject their own
insulin or check their blood glucose levels during their hospital stay.
The intention behind this requirement is to keep people safe. But if a person
needs insulin and it’s not administered at the correct time, this can impact
You can imagine the anxiety and helplessness people feel when they lose
control of their treatment and their body. Especially when they know the
Staying on a diabetes diet is yet another challenge for people in hospital,
because they have little or no say over what they eat, when and how much.
 **** One million people who visit Australian hospitals each year have
diabetes. Meaning 10% of hospital stays are people living with diabetes. They
are relying on staff to manage their condition – in addition to the illness
For children aged 14 and under living with type 1 diabetes, the
When someone comes to us with stories of diabetes management in hospital,
Rebekah Henricksen, Policy and Advocacy Manager, is the person who champions
She hears from people via calls to the Helpline, emails and social media. In
collaboration with other organisations, recurrent issues like this one are
raised with the decision-makers in government so they can be actioned for
“It’s not unusual to receive six to eight calls a day from people who are
concerned about the issues that surround their diabetes, and hospital care is
“Isolation is most commonly reported to us; people just feel like they’re
“People usually tell me about their problem in hospital by telephone and they
are very upset. Often people come to me in the late stages when a problem is
“Most of our hospital-based advocacy is more on the individual level, largely
because of the urgency of the circumstances. We guide people through the
“It’s about finding a mutually agreeable path, helping people living with
diabetes to get what they need. After our support, people generally don’t feel
the need to contact us for more help.”
## Tackling obstacles for people living with diabetes
Rebekah is involved in stakeholder working groups and committees, and makes
submissions and contributions to legislation whenever there is an opportunity.
They’ve been raising the issue of diabetes treatment in hospital with
representatives within the health system. The great news is that health and
other departments have now made it a priority to improve inpatient management
“Ultimately, our aim is to tackle the obstacles that make a person’s day-to-
“Diabetes is a medical diagnosis, but it comes with a whole raft of other
issues, largely as a result of the fact that people don’t understand diabetes.
My aim is to tackle those issues: discrimination, isolation, access to
services; and bring diabetes back as close as possible to simply a medical
